{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e3dc1dd6-4533-421f-9eb0-60afbca2139c","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open Console → sidebar → \"Crash Reports\" to browse them interactively.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash; the core file will appear at `/tmp/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`lldb`** — Attach after the fact or analyze a core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.12345 -- ./YourApp\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually the fastest path — it includes the faulting thread, stack trace, and signal info without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b7af736d-b148-4f87-9fb2-b54f581a4eb4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":334,"requestId":"D800:1F45CF:D1AFFA:F23F2F:69F2B52B"},"id":"8f31179a-a9cd-463f-9a7a-caaac6580682","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:49:46.417Z","parentId":"e181f842-90e9-4c7e-8dd9-72a95cf26dd0"}
